{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17471771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17471771"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:51:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:51:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"826"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"826","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/826"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.12,0.04,0.08,0.73]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"826"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102937"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"826","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/826"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"826"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85403"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"96"},{"type":"tags","id":"1122"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2661"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3007"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36275"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39658"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42161"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44033"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102937","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102937"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 17-year-old man is brought into the Emergency Department via ambulance with abdominal pain, confusion, and deep, gasping respirations. Collateral history from his parents reveals one month of fatigue and weakness with several absences from school, which is out of character. He has no medical history and takes no regular medications. A fingerprick glucose reveals a reading of 25.3 mmol/L.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following results would most likely be expected on arterial blood gas analysis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["pH of 7.51 (7.35 - 7.45)","pCO2 73 mmHg (35 - 45)","pO2 71 mmHg (80 - 100)","Bicarbonate 30 mmol/L (20 - 28)","Anion gap 33 (\u003C12)"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario describes diabetic ketoacidosis, which is characterised by hyperglycaemia, ketonaemia, and metabolic acidosis. The pH would be low, not high as in \u003Cstrong\u003EpH of 7.51\u003C/strong\u003E, due to the acidosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn an effort to compensate for the metabolic acidosis, the patient\u0027s respiratory drive is increased, causing hyperventilation, which would result in a low pCO2, not high as in \u003Cstrong\u003EpCO2 73 mmHg\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pO2 is typically normal or slightly low due to the respiratory compensation, but not as low as \u003Cstrong\u003EpO2 71 mmHg\u003C/strong\u003E unless there is another underlying respiratory issue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWith excess production of ketone bodies, bicarbonate levels would be expected to drop as it serves as a buffer, so \u003Cstrong\u003Ebicarbonate 30 mmol/L\u003C/strong\u003E would not be expected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn calculating the anion gap (Na\u207a + K\u207a) - (HCO3\u003Csup\u003E-\u003C/sup\u003E + Cl\u003Csup\u003E-\u003C/sup\u003E), a \u003Cstrong\u003Eraised anion gap\u003C/strong\u003E would be expected due to the presence of unmeasured anions such as ketones, making \u003Cstrong\u003Eanion gap 33\u003C/strong\u003E the correct answer. Other causes of high anion gap metabolic acidosis include lactate in sepsis or ischaemia and urea in renal failure.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A raised anion gap is a key feature of diabetic ketoacidosis, indicating the presence of unmeasured anions such as ketones.","Diabetic ketoacidosis is characterised by metabolic acidosis with compensatory respiratory alkalosis, leading to low bicarbonate and low pCO2.","Hyperglycaemia, ketonaemia, and metabolic acidosis are hallmark features of diabetic ketoacidosis."],"references":["Patel MP, Ahmed A, Gunapalan T, Hesselbacher SE. Use of sodium bicarbonate and blood gas monitoring in diabetic ketoacidosis: A review. World J Diabetes. 2018;9(11):199-205."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85403"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"826"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85403","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85403"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-17T15:57:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-17T15:58:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"826"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102937"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76",